SIMPLE: writhe
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Writhe
<hw>Writhe</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos>
<conjf>Writhed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Writhed</conjf>, <mark>Obs.</mark> or <mark>Poetic</mark>
<conjf>Writhen</conjf> <pr>(<?/)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Writhing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>writhen</ets>, AS.
<ets>wr⟦imac⟧<?/an</ets> to twist; akin to OHG. <ets>r⟦imac⟧dan</ets>,
Icel. <ets>r⟦imac⟧<?/a</ets>, Sw. <ets>vrida</ets>, Dan.
<ets>vride</ets>. Cf. <er>Wreathe</er>, <er>Wrest</er>,
<er>Wroth</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To twist; to turn; now, usually, to twist or turn so
as to distort; to wring.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧With <xex>writhing</xex> [turning]
of a pin.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Then Satan first knew pain,⟦br⟧
And <qex>writhed</qex> him to and fro.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Her mouth she <qex>writhed</qex>, her forehead taught to
frown.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His battle-<qex>writhen</qex> arms, and mighty hands.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To wrest; to distort; to pervert.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The reason which he yieldeth showeth the least part of his meaning
to be that whereunto his words are <qex>writhed</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To extort; to wring; to wrest.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark><-- ; extract -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The nobility hesitated not to follow the example of their
sovereign in <qex>writhing</qex> money from them by every species of
oppression.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Writhe</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Writhe
<hw>Writhe</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To twist or contort the body; to
be distorted; <as>as, to <ex>writhe</ex> with agony</as>. Also used
figuratively.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>After every attempt, he felt that he had failed, and
<qex>writhed</qex> with shame and vexation.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Writhen</ent>⟦br⟧
